, and the United States. Editors Molly Dunigan and Ulrich Petersohn argue that the global market for force is actually a conglomeration of many types of markets that vary according to local politics and geostrategic context. Each case study investigates the particular characteristics of the region's market, how each market evolved into its current form, and what consequence the privatized market may have for state military force and the provision of public safety. The comparative standpoint sheds light on better-known markets but also those less frequently studied, such as the state-owned and -managed security companies in China, militaries working for private sector extractive industries in Ecuador and Peru, and the ways warlord forces overlap with private security companies in Afghanistan.An invaluable resource for scholars and policymakers alike, The Markets for Force offers both an empirical analysis of variations in private military and security companies across the globe and deeper theoretical knowledge of how such markets develop.Contributors: Olivia Allison, Oldrich Bures, Jennifer Catallo, Molly Dunigan, Scott Fitzsimmons, Maiah Jaskoski, Kristina Mani, Carlos Ortiz, Ulrich Petersohn, Jake Sherman, Christopher Spearin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aPublic Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aAllison, Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvant, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBureš, Oldřich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatallo, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunigan, Molly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunigan, Molly, 